1.4 — Role-Based Authentication (JWT)
Personal note: One CustomUser model with a role field — no separate Profile models for each role. Store role and school_id inside the JWT payload so every API call carries the user's identity without extra DB lookups.

🔐  PROMPT 1.4A — Django Auth: CustomUser, JWT & Permissions
Working in: backend/accounts/

1. models.py — CustomUser(AbstractBaseUser, PermissionsMixin):
   email(unique, USERNAME_FIELD), first_name, last_name,
   school(FK tenants.School, null=True for superadmin),
   role(choices: superadmin|school_admin|teacher|student|parent),
   phone_number, profile_photo(URLField), is_active, date_joined,
   must_change_password(Bool, default=True)
   + CustomUserManager

2. permissions.py — DRF permission classes:
   IsSuperAdmin, IsSchoolAdmin, IsTeacher, IsStudent, IsParent
   Each checks: request.user.role == '...' AND
                request.user.school == request.tenant

3. serializers.py:
   LoginSerializer(email, password → validate + return tokens)
   UserProfileSerializer(all safe user fields)
   ChangePasswordSerializer

4. views.py:
   LoginView(POST /api/auth/login/)
     - Validates tenant membership
     - Returns: access, refresh, role, must_change_password, theme
   MeView(GET /api/auth/me/)
   ChangePasswordView(POST /api/auth/change-password/)
   TokenRefreshView (use simplejwt's)

5. Add to config/settings/base.py:
   AUTH_USER_MODEL = 'accounts.CustomUser'
   SIMPLE_JWT config: embed role + school_id in token payload
   INSTALLED_APPS: add 'accounts', 'rest_framework', 'corsheaders'
   REST_FRAMEWORK: default auth = JWTAuthentication

Run: python manage.py makemigrations accounts && python manage.py migrate

